<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="61.[151,1437,1275,2017]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1275,1301]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
[Based on the original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Dufek, M. I. &amp; Mulieri, P. R." box="[680,940,1276,1302]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" pagination="917 - 924" refId="ref107089" refString="Dufek, M. I. &amp; Mulieri, P. R. (2017) Two new species of Oxysarcodexia Townsend (Diptera: Sarcophagidae) from the Chaco Forest Ecoregion of South America. Journal of Medical Entomology, 54 (4), 917 - 924. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jme / tjx 054" type="journal article" year="2017">Dufek &amp; Mulieri 2017</bibRefCitation>
) and on photographs provided by Dr. Pablo R. Mulieri (MACN).] Male. Length 
<quantity box="[575,716,1311,1338]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.45" metricValueMax="8.5" metricValueMin="6.4" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" unit="mm" value="7.45" valueMax="8.5" valueMin="6.4">6.4–8.5 mm</quantity>
. Postocular plate with golden pollinosity. Ocellar bristles well developed. Thorax with silvery pollinosity. Four well-differentiated post-sutural dorsocentral bristles. Apical scutellar bristles absent. Legs blackish. Abdominal T1+2–T4 with silvery pollinosity, contrasting with the golden pollinosity of T5. T3 with 3 pairs of lateral marginal bristles, T4 with 3 pairs of lateral marginal bristles and with median marginal bristles (although the original description does not mention how many). ST5 with deep median V-shaped cleft, and scattered fine bristles on arms. Cercus slightly sinuous in lateral view with pointed obliquely cut apex and dorsal subapical barb, and, in posterior view, with a preapical pointed protuberance. Cercus with bristles ventrally in apical third. Cerci with distal third view broader than middle part in posterior view; parallel and with a distinct constriction mid length. Pregonite with expanded base, gradually narrowing to apex, which is darker. Postgonite with expanded base, suddenly narrowing to apex; unicolorous. Distiphallus with smooth ventroapical margin, square apex and dorsal sinuous outline. Juxta with lateral membranous folds, surface covered with microtrichia, and anterior juxtal margin serrated, with broad flake-like sclerotizations. Vesica symmetrical; distal lobes well developed, partially sclerotized (i.e., well sclerotized dorsally and membranous distally), large and sharply angled in lateral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="61" pageNumber="62" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="61.[151,1437,1275,2017]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1812,1838]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dufek &amp; Mulieri" authorityYear="2017" box="[325,561,1812,1838]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Oxysarcodexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ibera">
<emphasis box="[325,561,1812,1838]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Oxysarcodexia ibera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[579,677,1812,1838]" captionStart="FIGURES 139–147" captionStartId="62.[151,264,1837,1861]" captionTargetBox="[186,1406,331,1783]" captionTargetId="figure-70@62.[151,1435,308,1813]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 139–147. Oxysarcodexia spp., males. 139–141. Oxysarcodexia grandis Lopes (Colombia, Antioquia, Medellín, Cola del Zorro, CE-TdeA). 139. Habitus, lateral view. 140. Terminalia, lateral view. 141. Terminalia, posterior view. 142–144. Oxysarcodexia ibera Dufek &amp; Mulieri (Argentina, MACN). 142. Habitus, lateral view. 143. Terminalia, lateral view. 144. Terminalia, posterior view. 145–147. Oxysarcodexia inflata Lopes, paratype (Brazil, Maranhão, Rosário, Igarapé Paraqueú, MNRJ). 145. Habitus, lateral view. 146. Terminalia, lateral view. 147. Terminalia, posterior view. Figures 142–144 by P.R. Mulieri (MACN)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4405645" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4405645/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 143</figureCitation>
) may be considered closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Soares &amp; Mello-Patiu" authorityYear="2010" box="[1127,1229,1812,1838]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Oxysarcodexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitida">
<emphasis box="[1127,1229,1812,1838]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">O. nitida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1248,1346,1812,1839]" captionStart="FIGURES 192–200" captionStartId="79.[151,264,1717,1741]" captionTargetBox="[187,1406,210,1662]" captionTargetId="figure-17@79.[151,1435,181,1693]" captionTargetPageId="79" captionText="FIGURES 192–200. Oxysarcodexia spp., males. 192–194. Oxysarcodexia morretesi Tibana &amp; Mello, paratype (Brazil, São Paulo, Bertioga, MNRJ). 192. Habitus, lateral view. 193. Terminalia, lateral view. 194. Terminalia, posterior view. 195–197. Oxysarcodexia nitida Soares &amp; Mello-Patiu (Ecuador, Napo Province, NMR). 195. Habitus, lateral view. 196. Terminalia, lateral view. 197. Terminalia, posterior view. 198–200. Oxysarcodexia notata Soares &amp; Mello-Patiu (Ecuador, Napo Province, NMR). 198. Habitus, lateral view. 199. Terminalia, lateral view. 200. Terminalia, posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4405663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4405663/files/figure.png" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Fig. 196</figureCitation>
) due to similarities in phallic structures, especially the juxta, which does not fold backwards posteriorly, and in the similar dorsal part of the vesica. These two species can be separated by the anterior juxtal margin, which is conspicuous, broad, and flake-like in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Dufek &amp; Mulieri 2017)" baseAuthorityName="Dufek &amp; Mulieri" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[423,802,1919,1945]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Oxysarcodexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ibera">
<emphasis box="[423,517,1919,1945]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">O. ibera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dufek, M. I. &amp; Mulieri, P. R." box="[532,794,1919,1945]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" pagination="917 - 924" refId="ref107089" refString="Dufek, M. I. &amp; Mulieri, P. R. (2017) Two new species of Oxysarcodexia Townsend (Diptera: Sarcophagidae) from the Chaco Forest Ecoregion of South America. Journal of Medical Entomology, 54 (4), 917 - 924. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jme / tjx 054" type="journal article" year="2017">Dufek &amp; Mulieri 2017</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Female unknown. See also remarks under 
<taxonomicName authority="Souza &amp; Pape &amp; Thyssen, 2020" authorityName="Souza &amp; Pape &amp; Thyssen" authorityYear="2020" box="[1294,1436,1919,1945]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Oxysarcodexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ariozanoi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1294,1436,1919,1945]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">O. ariozanoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,215,1955,1981]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,215,1955,1981]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
